This is long enough for most of the flavourful stuff to be released into the water. The reason I say "most" is because there are some compounds that can only be removed by roasting meat (such as umami).  After letting it simmer for a while  strain out the beef and discard the bones/skin/etc. Then put in your vegetables. After about an hour or so  remove the vegetables and add your tomato paste. Finally  let it simmer for another half hour or so before serving.  This is my standard recipe for beef stew and it works well. The reason this doesn't work is because the collection is not immutable  meaning its contents can be changed.  To fix this error  create a wrapper class for your object and implement `IEnumerable<T>`. The class could look something like this:  ``` public class MyObjectWrapper : ObservableCollection<MyObject> {     public MyObjectWrapper()         : base()     {     } } ```  Then in your XAML file use the wrapper class instead of the original collection:  ``` <CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding MyList}" /> ```  Note that if you have already created the `MyObjectWrapper` class then you don't need to change anything else as the `CollectionView` will automatically bind to the collection. The binding code looks like this:  ``` DataContext = new MainWindow(); collection = new ObjectWrappedCollection<MyObject>(); dataContext.MyList = collection; ```  You may also want to consider using MVVM to make your life easier. There are some good tutorials about it here.  ## Answer (0)  Try changing your xaml code to  ``` <CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding MyList}" /> ```  Instead of  ``` <CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding MyObjectList}" />

This proverb is often used metaphorically when referring to projects like teamwork  collaboration  management  etc.  to illustrate how having too many cooks can lead to disorganization  conflict  wasted resources  loss of focus  and ultimately the failure of the undertaking.  However  this idiom doesn't mean one person must handle everything alone. It's better to find an optimal balance between independence and cooperation to achieve desired results. Too many cooks spoil the broth.  In a democracy  there should be no more than two co-equal powers: one elected executive and an independent judiciary. A third power of any kind is inimical to good administration.  To ensure that both branches of government perform their functions effectively and do not encroach onto each other's domain  it is essential that they have clear demarcation between them. In India  this has been achieved by having an Independent Election Commission which conducts elections independently of the Executive branch.  A federal system can help prevent overcentralization  but we must be careful to avoid its evils as well. The U.S Supreme Court rightly observed that 'The history of political parties shows that they tend to grow exponentially faster than a republican form of government can absorb or digest [20]. It cautions against multiparty systems and recommends keeping the number of recognized parties limited to 3 or 4 so that all are kept within manageable limits.  The ideal would therefore be a single strong centralized authority with some degree of devolution of powers  while at the same time ensuring checks and balances through multiple organs. This will call for separation of powers between legislatures and executives and between these and the courts. There should also be strict delineations between foreign policy and domestic policy matters.  Thus  the Indian Constitution has attempted such a model with mixed success. While it has had a strong centre for effective functioning  the states were given enough autonomy to develop on their own. However  the multiplicity of political parties and the frequent coalitions between parties have led to an unstable situation.  ## Conclusion  The basic premise of governance is that the people have the final say and that the rulers only implement what people want them to. To enable this  there must be a mechanism whereby the people can make known their wishes clearly
